snippet.textDisplay: First of all, it's a good song. And I'm sure there will be songs on the album that will contain more guitar and rock a little bit harder because this isn't really all that new for these guys. They always had a wide range putting out music: From loud and hard rocking to soft and beautiful ballads and from weird and alternative to pretty poppy. Take Re-arrange for example. The studio version hardly had guitars, but did the whole album sound like that? Nope! Wolves of Winter was much more loud and alternative and Howl was a catchy poprock song. I'm sure this album will also have that diversity.

snippet.textDisplay: Magnificent pop music! Massive production job but crystal clear natural vocal recording with just enough presence.The song sits well with Gary Go's "Wonderful", for example. I reckon there will be some cool dance mixes. "Hell hath no fury..." when did you last hear those words in a power-pop-rock song? In the chorus, the writer includes the listener with the words : "This is the sound that we make", rather than "i" or "you" . I love the opening line of each verse - "Dear God..." This is a musical letter or prayer to the man upstairs! "We can't unlearn what we've learned". Masterful lyrics! Like I said, as I reach the end of the 3,45 mins. Perfect pop music! Just love @Biffy Clyro!

That is the problem when people like to speculate. It's a band, a live organism that is always mutating. We musicians do music using what we are experiencing on our lives. The music has to grow, has to change and be great. Biffy Clyo so far is the most fascinating band on the rock scenario, they have the power of doing everything that want.

We have just to love it and be greatfull .
